<div class=3D"passage"><h2 id=3D"using-the-ellipse-calculator">Using the el=
lipse calculator</h2>

<p>The Monolithic Dome Institute Ellipse Calculator is a simple calculator =
for a deceptively complex shape. It will draw and calculate the area, circu=
mference, and foci for any size ellipse. It=E2=80=99s easy to use and easy =
to share results.</p>

<p>Input the major-radius, minor-radius, and the preferred units and press =
=E2=80=9CGo.=E2=80=9D It will draw the ellipse and output the calculations.=
 The page URL will save the values and can be bookmarked or shared with oth=
ers. Use the =E2=80=9CCopy to Clipboard=E2=80=9D to quickly copy and paste =
results in emails, messages, or research notes.</p>

<p><em>This calculator is subject to our <a href=3D"https://monolithicdome.=
com/tos">Terms of Service</a>.</em></p>
</div>
<div class=3D"image medium-container noalign-container">
<figure class=3D"medium noalign" id=3D"ellipse-diagram">
<a href=3D"https://monolithicdome.com/ellipse-calculator/fig/ellipse-diagra=
m"><img alt=3D"Diagram of ellipse calculator results." title=3D"Diagram of =
ellipse calculator results" itemprop=3D"contentUrl" src=3D"https://monolith=
icdome.com/vault/img/2020/09/22/5f696b353c0d9730c839e6cf/ellipse-diagram.me=
dium.webp" width=3D"1280" height=3D"864"></a>
<figcaption>
<div class=3D"caption"><p>Diagram of the default ellipse calculator results=
 with the major radius (a) and minor radius (b) plus one focal point (foci)=
.</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"credit"><a href=3D"https://monolithicdome.com/ellipse-calculato=
r/fig/ellipse-diagram">Dave South / Monolithic Commons / CC BY 4.0</a></p>
</figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<div class=3D"passage"><p><strong>Major radius.</strong> The major radius, =
the semi-major axis, or =E2=80=9Ca=E2=80=9D of the ellipse is the distance =
from the coordinate center to the furthest point on the ellipse. It is half=
 the major diameter, major-axis, or =E2=80=9CA=E2=80=9D of the ellipse.</p>

<p><strong>Minor radius.</strong> The minor radius, the semi-minor axis, or=
 =E2=80=9Cb=E2=80=9D of the ellipse is the distance from the coordinate cen=
ter to the closest possible point on the ellipse. It is half the minor diam=
eter, minor-axis, or =E2=80=9CB=E2=80=9D of the ellipse. The minor-axis is =
always perpendicular to the major axis.</p>

<p><strong>Circumference.</strong> The circumference is the perimeter aroun=
d the ellipse. There are many formulas developed to approximate the circumf=
erence with varying levels of accuracy. This calculator uses =E2=80=9CInfin=
ite Series 2=E2=80=9D found on the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/ge=
ometry/ellipse-perimeter.html">Math is Fun</a> website. It uses 20 binomial=
 coefficient terms for the approximation and is quite accurate for large el=
liptical footprints.</p>

<p><strong>Curvature.</strong> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Radius_of_curvature" title=3D"Wikipedia: Radius of curvature">radius of cu=
rvature</a> is a measure of the curve itself at the minor (b) vertex. The d=
istance is from the curve to an imaginary origin that would describe a circ=
le of that same curvature.</p>

<p><strong>Area.</strong> The area of the ellipse using the formula A =3D =
=CF=80ab.</p>

<p><strong>Foci.</strong> The distance from the coordinate center on the ma=
jor-axis=E2=80=94both directions=E2=80=94to the elliptical focal points. Us=
e the foci distance plus the pin and string method to draw an ellipse on pa=
per or on a job site.</p>

<p><strong>Units.</strong> The unit selection is for output formatting, onl=
y.</p>

<p><em>This calculator is subject to our <a href=3D"https://monolithicdome.=
com/tos">Terms of Service</a>.</em></p>
